 AA guns |Ship notes= }} |}
'''German submarine ''U-1195''''' was a [[German Type VII submarine|Type VIIC]] [[U-boat]] of [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]''.
Her [[Keel laying|keel was laid down]] 6 February 1943, by [[Schichau-Werke|F. Schichau]], of [[Danzig]]. She was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] 4 November 1943.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://uboat.net/boats/u1195.htm |title=The Type VIIC boat U-1195 |last=Helgason |first=Guðmundur |website=German U-boats of WWII - uboat.net |accessdate=8 December 2014 }}</ref>
==Design== [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIC|German Type VIIC submarines]] were preceded by the shorter [[German Type VII submarine#Type VIIB|Type VIIB submarines]]. ''U-1195'' had a displacement of {{convert|769|t|LT}} when at the surface and {{convert|871|t|LT}} while submerged.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} She had a total length of {{convert|67.10|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[pressure hull]] length of {{convert|50.50|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|6.20|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a height of {{convert|9.60|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a [[draught (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|4.74|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. The submarine was powered by two [[Germaniawerft]] F46 four-stroke, six-cylinder [[supercharged]] [[diesel engine]]s producing a total of {{convert|2800 to 3200|PS|kW shp|-1}} for use while surfaced, two [[AEG]] GU 460/8–27 [[Motor–generator|double-acting electric motors]] producing a total of {{convert|750|PS|kW shp}} for use while submerged. She had two shafts and two {{convert|1.23|m|ft|abbr=on|0}} [[propeller]]s. The boat was capable of operating at depths of up to {{convert|230|m}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
The submarine had a maximum surface speed of {{convert|17.7|kn}} and a maximum submerged speed of {{convert|7.6|kn}}.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}} When submerged, the boat could operate for {{convert|80|nmi}} at {{convert|4|kn}}; when surfaced, she could travel {{convert|8500|nmi}} at {{convert|10|kn}}. ''U-1195'' was fitted with five {{convert|53.3|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s (four fitted at the bow and one at the stern), fourteen [[torpedo]]es, one [[8.8 cm SK C/35 naval gun|{{convert|8.8|cm|in|2|abbr=on}} SK C/35 naval gun]], 220 rounds, and an anti-aircraft gun. The boat had a [[Ship's company|complement]] of between forty-four and sixty.{{sfn|Gröner|1991|pp=43-46}}
==Service history== Under the command of Ernst Cordes, she sank the {{SS|James Eagan Layne}}<ref>Dive South Cornwall, wreck of JEL, p43, [[Richard Larn]], ISBN 0-946020-25-6</ref> on 21 March 1945. Another account shows ''James Egan Layne'' was sunk by {{GS|U-399||2}}, and instead credits ''U-1195'' with the destruction of the [[Liberty Ship]] ''John R. Park''.<ref name=Uboat.net>{{citation |title=Patrol Data for ''U-1195'' |url=http://uboat.net/boats/successes/details.php?boat=1195 |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref><ref name="Innes McCartney 2002">{{cite book|author=Innes McCartney|title=Lost Patrols: Submarine Wrecks of the English Channel|year=2002}}</ref>
''U-1195'' attacked [[Convoy]] VWP 16 in the [[English Channel]], sinking the troop transport {{SS|Cuba|1923|6}}<ref name="ReferenceA">Dive Wight and Hampshire, Martin Pritchard and Kendal McDonald, ISBN 0-946020-15-9</ref> on 6 April 1945. She was sunk by one of the convoy{{'}}s escorts, the [[Royal Navy]] [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Watchman|D26}}, using a [[Hedgehog (weapon)|Hedgehog]] [[antisubmarine]] [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval-history.net/xGM-Chrono-10DD-09VW-Watchman.htm|title=HMS Watchman, destroyer|publisher=}}</ref> on 7 April 1945 to the southeast of the [[Isle of Wight]] at {{coord|50|33|22.26|N|0|56|17.81|W}} ([[WGS84]]) in 30 metres (98 feet) of water.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> Fifty crew members were alive when she sank; however, only 14 survived.<ref name="Innes McCartney 2002"/><ref name=USSubCasualties1966>{{cite journal |title=Submarine Casualties Booklet |publisher=U.S. Naval Submarine School |year=1966 |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/8200 |accessdate=2009-09-08}}</ref>
